#RG #Regram @NOAAFisheries: #OrcaMonth -- Southern Resident Killer Whales are noticeably different from both transient and offshore forms. Their dorsal fin is rounded at the tip and curved/tapering, or "falcate". All resident killer whales primarily eat fish and occur in large social groups called "pods," groups of whales that are seen in association with one another over 50% of the time. The pods represent collections of matrilines, their fundamental social unit.
Southern Resident Killer Whales are the only resident form to occur in contiguous U.S. waters and they comprise the smallest distinct population segment (DPS) of resident killer whales in the world with only about 81 individuals currently. Learn more about them here on our #NOAASpotlightSpecies page: http://1.usa.gov/1NgDQkr

#RG Regram @NatGeo: Photograph by @paulnicklen for @natgeo // What is your spirit animal? I have many, but this encounter with the elusive, rare, and shy Kermode Bear (or Spirit Bear) was one of the most beautiful and powerful experiences I have ever had in nature. After weeks and months of searching, I came upon this bear fishing in a stream. Instead of being scared and running away, this bear was completely relaxed and allowed me to step into his world and capture intimate moments that help connect people to a fragile and magnificent landscape that needs protection. That is how I knew he was one of my spirit animals. With @jedweingarten and @cristinamittermeier #nature #bear #spiritbear #kermodebear #wildlife @natgeocreative @thephotosociety #beauty #keepexploring #letsexplore #love #follow #instagood #photooftheday #picoftheday #instagramhub

#Regram RG @everydayclimatechange: The Climate Reality Project's Creative Director Peter Yesawich Jr @pyesawichjr shot this photo of one of Manila's most polluted rivers. The Philippines is considered as one of the most vulnerable countries to climate change. With impacts ranging from extreme weather events and periodic inundation to droughts and food scarcity, climate change has been a constant reality that many Filipinos have had to face. Most vulnerable are those residing in coastal communities and the lower-rung urban communities that lack awareness on climate change adaptation.The Philippines is home to over 100 million people. The population impact places stress on resources and urban development.

#Regram RG @NatGeo: Photo by @amivitale. Meet Kitui. This adorable baby black rhino is evidence of Lewa Wildlife Conservancys (@lewa_wildlife) success in protecting a species desperately threatened by poaching. There are now four hand-raised baby black rhinos in Lewa, all being carefully and lovingly guarded by rangers who love these little guys like their own children. The rhino are being handraised for different reasons  one is blind, another was orphaned after poachers killed his mother, and two others are born to a blind mother who abandons them after birth.
The black rhino is critically endangered, and every individual animal counts in saving the species.

Who's the most chill mom ever lighting candles? Big thanks to my husband for capturing a face I never knew existed. Cake was a hit. Obvi.

Here's me with the cake so you can understand the size! Cake details: because I was working this week, I totally just used boxed yellow mix and premade chocolate frosting. I know that's cheating but I honestly just didn't have the time! Also, Birdie, Marc and my mom had to actually bake the cakes while I was shooting. It took 4 whole cake mixes but I did have a bunch of scraps left over. I followed Ann Reardon's tutorial on You Tube and bought her templates on Howtocookthat.net which worked really well, although I did have to improvise a bit, it's not exactly as she did it. Birdie and I both found her voice to be super soothing though, FYI. The bubble guppies and George are all plastic figurines because while I originally was planning to sculpt them, I had to compromise for time/sanity! Plus, Cricket will be happy to play with them after the cake is eaten!! I used a combo of Wilton and Duff fondant.(Cc: @howtocookthat)

She asked for Thomas with Bubble Guppies as passengers. I threw in Curious George cause I figured he wouldn't want to be left out... I'll post more pics of the cake tomorrow. Right now, I just have to sleep. Caking is exhausting.

Cricket requested a Thomas the Train cake with Bubble Guppies riding it for her birthday party this weekend- I started making the train details yesterday. I found an amazing website called Howtocookthat.net where a lady named Ann Reardon has templates and tutorials for a bunch of different amazing 3D cakes- AND! she had a Thomas cake tutorial. Anyway, I highly recommend checking it out if you're into cakes- in all my 3D cake baking, I somehow had never seen her website. I will post more pics tomorrow when I assemble it!!

Spot the tiny baby boots! They were knitted by members of the Cambrian Mountains Wool Project, which aims to help sustain the traditional upland farms and rural communities of Wales.  The woollen boots were given to The Prince of Wales today as a gift for his granddaughter Princess Charlotte. The Cambrian Mountains Wool Project is part of the Cambrian Mountains Initiative, of which His Royal Highness is President. #WalesWeek

After celebrating his second-round win against Robin Hasse, @andymurray threw his wristband into the crowd. It was caught by Wimbledon Chairman, Philip Brook and presented to HRH The Duchess of Cornwall. 
The Duchess of Cornwall is today giving #Wimbledon (and Andy Murray) fans a chance to bid for this prize souvenir by donating the item to auction. All proceeds will go to the Royal Veterinary College Animal Care Trust, a charity which supports not-for-profit hospitals run by the Royal Veterinary College, as well as the colleges pioneering research and education programmes. 
This year marks the 10th anniversary of Her Royal Highness's patronage of the charity and it was personally selected by Andy Murray as the beneficiary of this auction. This is a unique opportunity to bid for a piece of #Wimbledon history. Follow the link in our profile.

The Queen and members of the Royal Family and the Middleton family together at Sandringham House after Princess Charlotte's christening.

Glorious views across the Vale of Usk and Brecon Beacons can be enjoyed from the gardens of High Glau Manor in Monmouth, Wales. The Manor is an Arts & Crafts style house set in 12 acres of gardens. Owner Helena Gerrish gave The Prince of Wales a tour of the gardens and its unique features today. #WalesWeek

This cake has been made to commemorate The Prince of Wales's visit to High Glanau Manor in Monmouth, Wales. The cake features an original piece on High Glanau that was published in a 1929 issue of Country Life magazine. #WalesWeek
Her Royal Highness with Owen Teale at a musical evening at their Welsh home
This is the official brooch which can be worn by The Prince of Wales's harpist.
HRH meets Anne Denholm the new official harpist to The Prince of Wales

During today's visit to Llandovery in Wales, The Duchess of Cornwall became a member of the Llandovery Women's Institute (WI). The WI was formed in 1915 and provides women with educational opportunities and the chance to learn new skills. HRH is already a member of the Tetbury WI. #WalesWeek

The Prince of Wales dances with performers during the International Musical #Eisteddfod in Llangollen, Wales. The Eisteddfod is a celebration of music, dance, costume and culture from nations around the world. #WalesWeek

The scenic town of Llangollen in North Wales hosts the International Musical #Eisteddfod each year. Around 4,000 performers take part in this cultural festival of competitive song and dance. The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall will watch the annual International Parade today, which features hundreds of competitors parading through the streets of the mountain town in national costumes. #WalesWeek

Wern Isaf in Llanfairfechan, Wales, is a beautiful early 20th century house built in the Arts and Crafts style. The tiles on this original fireplace in Wern Isaf house have been individually fired, given them their distinct colouring. The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall toured Wern Isaf today #WalesWeek
HRH met traditional clog maker Trefor Owen and his apprentice Gwilym Rhys at a reception on day one of #WalesWeek
The Prince of Wales today met author John Pikoulis. John presented HRH with a copy of his biography of Alun Lewis, the famous Welsh poet whose centenary is marked this year #WalesWeek

The Prince of Wales is shown a mug commemorating his 1969 Investiture at Caernarfon Castle during a visit to the 'Too Good To Waste' recycling charity and social enterprise in Ynyshir, Wales. The charity reduces waste by collecting re-usable household items and redistributing them via its charity showrooms. The charity was set up 20 years ago with help from The Prince's Trust. The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall began their annual visit to Wales today. #WalesWeek

Today The Duchess of Cornwall visited #Wimbledon and met ball boys, ball girls and Armed Forces personnel who are acting as stewards for The Championships. The Duchess also met tennis player Rafael Nadal and watched British competitor Andy Murray win his match.
The Band of the Brigade of Gurkhas perform as part of the Beating Retreat at 2nd Battalion The Royal Gurkha Rifles in Folkestone, Kent. The Prince of Wales took the salute during the event.

For today's visit to the 2nd Battalion Royal Gurkha Rifles, The Prince of Wales wore the 2nd Gurkha Regimental Association Bicentenary medal, the Royal Gurkha Rifles badge and tie and the UK Veterans badge.

Girls dressed in traditional Nepalese clothing wait to greet The Prince of Wales at the 2nd Battalion The Royal Gurkha Rifles in Folkestone, Kent. 2015 marks 200 years of #Gurkha service to the Crown and tonight The Prince will attend the Beating Retreat. HRH has been Colonel in Chief of The Royal Gurkha Rifles since 1977.
The Prince of Wales visits the Combined Operations Pilotage Parties Memorial on Hayling Island in Hampshire. HRH is Patron of the COPP Heroes Memorial Fund.
